creates useful `height_le` and `length_le_height` lemmas to show inequalities involving `height`.

From the Carleson project.

```suggestion
  apply le_antisymm _ (biSup_mono fun _ => le_of_eq)
```
and that saves you from half the proof
Accident?

No, see the PR description: As I was updating the development I found that the `height_le(_iff)` lemma is simply not needed anywhere, but I do often need to prove `height x ≤ n` and the stronger assumption (with the equality) is helpful.

I guess I could phrase this as an `iff` lemma, and use with `.mpr`, but what’s the point of an iff lemma if you only ever use one direction (for the other direction, it’s usually better to have the inquality, as that’s more general.

> I guess I could phrase this as an `iff` lemma, and use with `.mpr`, but what’s the point of an iff lemma if you only ever use one direction (for the other direction, it’s usually better to have the inquality, as that’s more general.

It's the universal property of `height`. That seems rather important!

Whenever I define some kind of supremum/infimum, the universal property is the single most useful lemma in all of its API.
Yeah, I had them originally. Will put them back. And I guess I'll just include both variants (with = and with ≤), maybe more efficient than trying to guess which ones will actually be needed.

Can you turn this into an iff?
```suggestion
lemma height_eq_index_of_length_eq_height_last {p : LTSeries α}
    p.length = height p.last ↔ ∀ i, height (p i) = i := by
```

Yes, but is that useful? The other direction is a triviality and would hold for any function, not just `height`

I have a sense that you value `iff` lemmas more than I do, maybe I am missing something about their usefulness and ergonomics (besides when they are nice as rewriting rules) – what am I missing?
They can be used in `simp` and `rw`! That's the main appeal to me

Hmm, but rewrite rules that have equalities as their `lhs`, are they commonly useful? I wouldn’t expect, say, the equality `p.length = height p.last` to appear a lot nested inside some goal so that one would want to reach for rewriting?

I do expect that maybe one wants to rewrite `height (p i)` to `i` using `rw`, but then you does the original formulation as an implications, so that `height (p i)` is the lhs of the rule?

> rewrite rules that have equalities as their `lhs`, are they commonly useful?

Yes, I certainly use them often

> I wouldn’t expect, say, the equality `p.length = height p.last` to appear a lot nested inside some goal so that one would want to reach for rewriting?

That might be true. I don't really know what to expect here
eg these uses of the `iSup₂` API show that your API for `height` is lacking

Hmm, yes, but the reason is that I am building the basic API here. Maybe it would be cleaner to define the ”stronger” `height_le` first (which is the second part of this proof) and then build this equality next. Will try when at the computer next.

There is the tension that `height` has two similar definitions (eq or < in the condition), and some lemmas are more useful with the one form and some others with the other form (and I'd say it's helpful to only have the more useful variant)

> (and I'd say it's helpful to only have the more useful variant)

I would say this is true only when one lemma clearly has a strictly more useful form. The universal property is not clearly more useful one way or the other since it is by definition used both forward and backward
Right - and because I couldn't decide which of the two is more useful, and because it seems that it was unused in my development, I removed both. But will just put both back.

```suggestion
    height a ≤ n ↔ ∀ ⦃p : LTSeries α⦄, p.last ≤ a → p.length ≤ n := by
```
for usability

```suggestion
    height a ≤ n ↔ ∀ ⦃p : LTSeries α⦄, p.last = a → p.length ≤ n := by
```
